{"id":"bd-abc","title":"New title",...}
>>>>>>> branch-name
```

Normal git mergetools don't understand beads merge semantics (LWW by updated_at).

## Go beads solution

`bd resolve-conflicts` command that:
1. Parses conflict markers in JSONL
2. Applies beads merge semantics (updated_at wins, arrays merge, etc.)
3. Writes resolved JSONL atomically
4. Supports dry-run and JSON output

## Implementation approach

**Core conflict parsing** (`src/merge/conflict_parser.rs`):
```rust
#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct ConflictRegion {
    pub start_line: usize,
    pub end_line: usize,
    pub left_side: Vec<String>,   // Between <<<<<<< and =======
    pub right_side: Vec<String>,  // Between ======= and >>>>>>>
    pub left_label: String,        // e.g., "HEAD"
    pub right_label: String,       // e.g., "branch-name"
}

pub fn parse_conflicts(content: &str) -> Result<(Vec<ConflictRegion>, Vec<String>)> {
    let mut conflicts = Vec::new();
    let mut clean_lines = Vec::new();
    let mut in_conflict = false;
    let mut current_region: Option<ConflictRegion> = None;

    for (line_num, line) in content.lines().enumerate() {
        if line.starts_with("<<<<<<<") {
            // Start of conflict
            in_conflict = true;
            current_region = Some(ConflictRegion {
                start_line: line_num,
                left_label: line[7..].trim().to_string(),
                ..Default::default()
            });
        } else if line.starts_with("=======") && in_conflict {
            // Switch to right side
            // ...
        } else if line.starts_with(">>>>>>>") && in_conflict {
            // End of conflict
            current_region.right_label = line[7..].trim().to_string();
            conflicts.push(current_region.take().unwrap());
            in_conflict = false;
        } else if !in_conflict {
            clean_lines.push(line.to_string());
        } else {
            // Inside conflict, accumulate
            // ...
        }
    }

    Ok((conflicts, clean_lines))
}
```

**Conflict resolution** (`src/merge/conflict_resolver.rs`):
```rust
pub enum ResolutionMode {
    Mechanical,     // Use LWW rules automatically
    Interactive,    // Prompt user (future)
}

pub struct ConflictResolver {
    mode: ResolutionMode,
}

impl ConflictResolver {
    pub fn resolve(&self, region: &ConflictRegion) -> Result<Vec<String>> {
        match self.mode {
            ResolutionMode::Mechanical => self.resolve_mechanical(region),
            ResolutionMode::Interactive => unimplemented!("Interactive mode"),
        }
    }

    fn resolve_mechanical(&self, region: &ConflictRegion) -> Result<Vec<String>> {
        // Parse JSONL from both sides
        let left_issues = self.parse_jsonl(&region.left_side)?;
        let right_issues = self.parse_jsonl(&region.right_side)?;

        // Build issue map by ID
        let mut merged = HashMap::new();

        for issue in left_issues {
            merged.insert(issue.id.clone(), issue);
        }

        for issue in right_issues {
            if let Some(existing) = merged.get(&issue.id) {
                // Same ID - merge using LWW rules
                let resolved = merge_issues(existing, &issue)?;
                merged.insert(issue.id.clone(), resolved);
            } else {
                // New issue from right
                merged.insert(issue.id.clone(), issue);
            }
        }

        // Serialize back to JSONL
        let mut lines = Vec::new();
        for issue in merged.values() {
            lines.push(serde_json::to_string(issue)?);
        }

        Ok(lines)
    }

    fn parse_jsonl(&self, lines: &[String]) -> Result<Vec<Issue>> {
        lines.iter()
            .filter(|line| !line.is_empty())
            .map(|line| serde_json::from_str(line))
            .collect()
    }
}
